# Takeaway

The key idea is to treat the binary tree as a **Complete Binary Tree** by assigning an index to every node. During **Level Order BFS**, record the index of the first and last node in each level. The width of that level is calculated as:

```text
lastIndex - firstIndex + 1
```

To avoid integer overflow in deep trees, normalize the indexes at each level by subtracting the first index before processing child nodes. This approach efficiently computes the maximum width in **O(n)** time.
